05178nam a22007815i 9780814788493DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147884937 a10.18574/97808147884932doi  a(DE-B1597)547408  a(OCoLC)893740350  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPN4885.I8bV45 2016 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a071.3089512231 aVellon, Peter G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Great Conspiracy against Our Race :bItalian Immigrant Newspapers and the Construction of Whiteness in the Early 20th Century /cPeter G. Vellon. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2014] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCulture, Labor, History ;v500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Italian language press and the creation of an Italian racial identity -- t2. The Italian language press and Africa -- t3. Native Americans, Asians, and Italian Americans: constructions of a multilayered racial consciousness -- t4. The education of Italian Americans in matters of color -- t5. Defending Italian American civility, asserting whiteness -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAbout the author 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRacial history has always been the thorn in America's side, with a swath of injustices-slavery, lynching, segregation, and many other ills-perpetrated against black people. This very history is complicated by, and also dependent on, what constitutes a white person in this country. Many of the European immigrant groups now considered white also had to struggle with their own racial identities. In A Great Conspiracy against Our Race, Peter Vellon explores how Italian immigrants, a once undesirable and "swarthy" race, assimilated into dominant white culture through the influential national and radical Italian language press in New York City. Examining the press as a cultural production of the Italian immigrant community, this book investigates how this immigrant press constructed race, class, and identity from 1886 through 1920. Their frequent coverage of racially charged events of the time, as well as other topics such as capitalism and religion, reveals how these papers constructed a racial identity as Italian, American, and white. A Great Conspiracy against Our Race vividly illustrates how the immigrant press was a site where socially constructed categories of race, color, civilization, and identity were reworked, created, contested, and negotiated. Vellon also uncovers how Italian immigrants filtered societal pressures and redefined the parameters of whiteness, constructing their own identity. This work is an important contribution to not only Italian American history, but America's history of immigration and race.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aImmigrantsxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aImmigrantszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aItalian American newspapersxHistoryx20th century. 0aItalian American newspapersxHistoryy20th century. 0aItalian AmericansxCultural assimilationxHistoryx20th century. 0aItalian AmericansxCultural assimilationxHistoryy20th century. 0aItalian AmericansxRace identityxHistoryx20th century. 0aItalian AmericansxRace identityxHistoryy20th century. 0aItalian AmericansxSocial conditionsx20th century. 0aItalian AmericansxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aWhitesxRace identityxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aWhitesxRace identityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z9783110711875